en: Der sinnreiche Junker Don Quixote von La Mancha
Der sinnreiche Junker Don Quixote von La Mancha.
1.1 DQ at his library reading chivalric novels
Don Quixote at his library reading chivalric books; several books and arms all around the room.Acceptable engraving, but not good enough to copy all the details from the original illustration.
1 - Schrödter's illus., although dated in 1843, first appeared as a set of six prints in an illustrated wrapper in Altona/Leipzig: G. Mayer (printed in Leipzig by G. Kreysing), 1863.
Alonso Quijano talks about chivalric novels to the priest and the barber

Alonso Quijano talks about chivalric books to the barber, maese Nicolás, and the priest.Scene resolved with great naturalism; don Quixote, standing up and holding a book, with gesture of discussing with the barber about which one is the best knight (barber's gesture is remarkable too); the priest observes don Quixote.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
1.2 Alonso Quixano (AQ) becomes the knight Don Quixote de la Mancha (DQ)1.3 AQ names self DQ, his horse (Rocinante), and lady (Dulcinea)
Alonso Quixono loses his mind and becomes the Knigh Don Quixote de la Mancha; he appears at his library, drawing his sword, surrounded by arms and with a book fallen onto the floor.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote's dinner at the inn

The innkeeper helps don Quixote to drink with a cane through his helmet; both party girls observe him.Scene resolved with naturalism (see the figures of both "ladies"), good drawing and agile engraving.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote encounters Juan Haldudo whipping Andrés

Well-known scene; don Quixote (background; just sketched) finds Juan Haldudo whipping Andrés (foreground).Juan Haldudo's gesture is not quite well-resolved; but the contrary, Andrés' figure, extremely realistic, is very remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote finds the silk merchants of Toledo
4.4 Adventure of the merchants from Toledo

Don Quixote encounters the silk merchants of Toledo; see the different use of engraving for foreground figures (don Quixote and Rocinante; well-marked) and background figures (the merchants; just sketched).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote is taken back to home by Pedro Alonso
5.1 End of first sally5.2 DQ rescued by Pedro Alonso5.3 DQ returns home

Well-known scene; Pedro Alonso takes don Quixote back to his home; the knight appears on Pedro Alonso's donkey and Rocinante carries don Quixote's arms and broken lance.Don Quixote, in conversation with Pedro Alonso, mistakes him with several characters from chivalric books.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.

Don Quixote's second sally; the first with Sancho.This is one of the best known images of the universal literature; the knight riding Rocinante and the squire his donkey with their village in the background.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
The Basque lady asks don Quixote to forgive the Basque's life

The Basque lady, accompanied by another one, kneels down before don Quixote and asks him not to hurt the Basque (fallen in the background).Don Quixote and the Basque lady's figures have been highlighted by a precise drawing and engraving, while the second lady and the Basque remain sketched.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.2 Grisóstomo´s song
Vivaldo gets ready to read Grisóstomo's song.Grisóstomo's corpse surrounded by shepherds (some of them kelt down, with sobbing faces), don Quixote, Ambrosio and Vivaldo; quite dramatic scene.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
14.1 Episode of Grisóstomo and Marcela, continuation14.3 Marcela’s appearance and speech

Appearance of Marcela.Very well-resolved scene with a vertical composition (accurate to Cervantes' text, Marcela has to appear over some rocks); the scene, with an almost shining Marcela and the shepherds knelt down, reminds the traditional representation ofThe Announcement to the Shepherds.The figures of the shepherds (see their gestures and faces) are quite remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote fights with the Yanguesan carriers

Fight among don Quixote, Sancho and the Yanguesan carriers.Well resolved-scene, with a small goup of well-drawn and engraved figures in the foreground (don Quixote, Sancho and three yangüeses; another two just sketeched) and a larger group, just sketched, in the background.Figures with good movements.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
17.2 Balsam of Fierabrás taken by DQ and SP
Don Quixote prepares the Balsam of Fierabás observed by Sancho, the innkeeper and the cuadrillero.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote and Sancho observing two armies/flocks of sheep
18.1 Adventure of the flock of sheep (rebaños)

From the top of a hill, don Quixote explains to Sancho (see don Quixote's hand and Sancho's face) who are the Knights of two armies; Johannot has not represented the flock of sheep (just a dust cloud in the background), so we do not know yet if it is really an army or a flock of sheep.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
20.1 Adventure of the fulling mills (batanes)20.3 SP’s tricks DQ
Frightened by the noise of falling strokes, iron chains and water, Sancho stops don Quixote beginning a new adventure tying Rocinante's legs.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote asking a soldier about the galley-slaves
22.1 Adventure of the galley slaves (galeotes)22.2 Dialogue with galeotes

In the foreground, well-drawn and engraved, Sancho, don Quixote and a soldier; in the background, the group of galley-slaves with a pair of soldiers; some of the galley-slaves can be identified (Ginés de Pasamonte, the old man...).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote and Sancho stoned by the galley-slaves
22.1 Adventure of the galley slaves (galeotes)22.4 Liberation of galeotes
In the foreground, don Quixote and Sancho protect themselves from the stones thrown by the galley slaves from the background.Sancho's face is quite remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Don Quixote and Sancho find a dead mule
23.1 DQ and SP enter Sierra Morena
In Sierra Morena, don Quixote and Sancho find a dead mule; Johannot does not offer a too much detailed image, what would be gloomy.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Sancho cuts some branches of broom to use them to find his way back.Drawing and engraving are quite remarkable because of the naturalism of the figure.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.

After encountering the priest and the barber, Sancho, who does not want to go into the inn where he was blanketed, asks them to give him something to eat outside.Figure drawn and engraved with great naturalism.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
Luscinda giving a letter for Cardenio
27.2 Cardenio’s tells story (Don Fernando and Luscinda)
Reference to Cardenio's story; Luscinda asks a man to carry a letter to Cardenio; accurate to Cervantes' text: "una señora muy hermosa le llamó desde una ventana, los ojos llenos de lágrimas" (27:1).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
28.1 Priest, barber and Cardenio encounter Dorotea

After being surprised, Dorotea tries to run away, but she falls down and the priest arrives calming her down.The scene is very well resolved; Dorotea and the priest's gestures are specially remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836.
The public crier offering a reward to anyone who could find Dorotea
Dorotea tells her story to the priest, the barber and Cardenio; the public crier offers a great reward to anyone who could find Dorotea; then, she decides to run away.Scene resolved with realism.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Tender scene; Sancho recovers his donkey.Drawing and engraving are of quality, and the figures are represented with great realism.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote, Sancho, the barber, the priest, Cardenio and Micomicona eating
Don Quixote, Sancho, the barber, the priest, Cardenio and Micomicona eating by the side of a small spring; bucholic scene.The variety of their gestures and naturalism are remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The priest beginning to read the novel of El Curioso Impertinente
33.1 Reading at inn of the tale of El curioso impertinente (Anselmo, Lotario and Camila)

The scene has been resolved with the realism characteristic of a genre scene; the priest begins to read the novel of "The Ill-Advised Curiosity" before Dorotea, Cardenio, the barber, Sancho, the innkeeper, his wife and Maritornes.The variety of gestures is remarkable (see Dorotea).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
33.1 Reading at inn of the tale of El curioso impertinente (Anselmo, Lotario and Camila)
Anselmo leaves Camila and Lotario alone; a very accurate detail from Cervantes' text: "lo que hizo fue poner el codo sobre el brazo de la silla" (33:1).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The innkeeper hits don Quixote, who was attacking his wineskins.The figures are resolved with nervous and quick drawing/engraving lines, looking like sketched.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote continues believing that Dorotea is the Princess Micomicona

Don Quixote argues before Dorotea, Luscinda, don Fernando, Cardenio and others, that, despite what Sancho has told him, he believes that Dorotea is still the Princess Micomicona, but transformed by an enchanter. Also Sancho, observing don Quixote quiet.Don Quixote's figure is remarkable and especially comical.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Captive's father giving his blessing to his sons
39.1 Episode of the captive39.2 Captive’s tale

Reference to the captive's tale; every brother chooses his career: serving the king, commerce and studying letters.In the illustration, the father kisses the youngest son, who has chosen to study letters in Salamanca.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
39.1 Episode of the captive39.2 Captive’s tale
Reference to captive's tale; some Arabs cut Pagano Doria's head off .The scene includes some elements quite in keeping with Romaticism taste (Orientalism, tragedy, treachery...).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The renegade asking for fruit to Zoraida's father

Reference to captive's tale; the renegade "se iba al jardín de Zoraida y le pedía fruta, y su padre se la daba sin conocelle" (41:1).Orientalist scene in keeping with Romaticism taste; see clothes, setting...
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
A coach arriving to the inn
42.1 Arrival of judge (oidor) and lady (Clara) at inn

Accurate to Cervantes' text, a coach attended by some men on horseback arrives to the inn demmanding accommodation to the innkeeper.Drawing and engraving are simple, without details, but the setting is well-suggested.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.

Excellent representation of don Quixote mounting guard in the inn; "don Quijote se salió fuera de la venta a hacer la centinela del castillo, como lo había prometido" (42:1).Drawing, engraving and shading are carefully done; don Quixote's expression is masterly.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote holding the barber basin
44.3 Beginning of the dispute about the packsaddle

Don Quixote begins the defence of his barber basin as Mambrino's helmet (see his gesture): "Miren vuestras mercedes con qué cara podía decir este escudero que ésta es bacía, y no el yelmo que yo he dicho; y juro por la orden de caballería que profeso que este yelmo fue el mismo que yo le quité, sin haber añadido en él ni quitado cosa alguna" (44:1).Drawing and engraving are good.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote is "enchanted" (tied) and taken into a cage by "phantoms" (don Luis' servants, don Fernando and his companions and the innkeeper disguised).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote leaving the inn enchanted

The landlady, her daughter and Maritornes pretend to be very afflicted when don Quixote leaves the inn "enchanted" in a cage on an oxcart.Don Quixote's image, sticking his head out through the cage bars, is quite comical.Both oxen are not represented with realism.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The priest allows don Quixote to go out of the cage
The priest and the canon let don Quixote go out of the cage; also one of the officers.The figure of the officer, with his back turned on the viewer, is probably the most remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Vicente de la Rosa playing the guitar
51.1 Tale of cabrero (Eugenio) about Leandra’s seduction and abandonment by Vicente de la Rosa

Reference to Eugenio's tale; accurate representation of Vicente de la Rosa playing the guitar; "Añadiósele a estas arrogancias ser un poco músico y tocar una guitarra a lo rasgado, de manera que decían algunos que la hacía hablar" (51:1).This image, with certain melancholy air, is quite in keeping with Romanticism taste.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.

After having been beaten by one of the penitents, don Quixote lies almost dead; Sancho, knelt by his side, weeps; "¡Oh flor de la caballería, que con sólo un garrotazo acabaste la carrera de tus tan bien gastados años!" (52:1).Image of great tenderness.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.

Sancho and his donkey.Drawing and engraving are excellent; the figures, almost without setting, perfectly detailed and characterized; see Sancho's face, looking directly to the viewer; it is not only a physionomical portrait, but a psychological too.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.2 - Placed as frontispiece.

Reference to one of the mad tales; when a licenciate is going to be released from the madhouse of Sevilla, confesses to a chaplain: "No tenga vuestra merced pena, señor mío, ni haga caso de lo que este loco ha dicho, que si él es Júpiter y no quisiere llover, yo, que soy Neptuno, el padre y el dios de las aguas, lloveré todas las veces que se me antojare y fuere menester" (1:2).The figure of the licenciate (see his gesture) is especially well-resolved.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho with the bachelor Sansón Carrasco
3.1 Sansón Carrasco visits DQ to tell him about the publication of his story, DQ Part I
Sancho returns with the bachelor Sansón Carrasco.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sansón Carrasco kneeling before don Quixote
4.1 Conversation among DQ, SP and Sansón Carrasco
Don Quixote, in bed, receives Sansón Carrasco's visit, who, after arriving with Sancho, kneels before the knight.The whole scene is resolved with a very free drawing, as sketched.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
5.1 SP speaks with his wife Teresa

End of the dialogue between Sancho and his wife Teresa Panza; "Y, en esto, comenzó a llorar tan de veras como si ya viera muerta y enterrada a Sanchica" (5:2).Both figures, carefully drawn and engraved, are especially tender.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho find a labourer in El Toboso
9.1 DQ and SP arrive to El Toboso

In El Toboso, don Quixote and Sancho find a labourer, to whom don Quixote asks if he knows where Dulcinea lives.The main figure of the scene is this labourer, whipping on his mules (picturesque); he appears well-drawn and engraved in the foreground, while don Quixote and Sancho remain sketched in the background.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho taking a rest in his way to El Toboso
10.1 SP goes in search of Dulcinea
Sancho waiting and napping near to El Toboso.Drawing and engraving are excellent.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Rocinante fallen down
11.1 Adventure of the cart of actors; “cortes de la muerte”

After being frightened by thebojiganga, Rocinante sets off across the plain with don Quixote mounted on him and, finally, he and the knight fall on the ground; "ordinario fin y paradero de las lozanías de Rocinante y de sus atrevimientos" (11:2).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
15.1 Identity and motives of knight of Mirrors are revealed (Sansón Carrasco)
Sansón Carrasco, defeated by don Quixote, returns to his home and is cured by a bone-setter; on the right, Tomé Cecial.Illustration resolved as a small genre scene.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The squeezed curds running all over don Quixote's face

Don Quixote thrusts his helmet down upon his head without knowing that Sancho has put some curds in it; when the curds are squeezed, don Quixote believes that his brains are melting.Don Quixote's face, very expressive, is quite remarkable
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote meets don Diego de Miranda's wife and son
18.1 DQ arrives at Don Diego’s house18.2 DQ meets Don Diego’s son Lorenzo

Don Diego introduces don Quixote to his wife, doña Cristina, and son, don Lorenzo.Figures are drawn and engraved with great delicacy (see don Quixote and doña Cristina's gestures, don Lorenzo's figure...).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho leaving don Diego's house
Don Quixote and Sancho leave don Diego's house.Accurate to Cervantes' text, there is a coat of arms over the street door.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
A cook offers Sancho a spoon with hens and geese
During Camacho's wedding, a cook offers Sancho a spoon with three hens and a couple of geese.Both figures are well resolved, but the one of the cook is much better (Sancho's figure looks artificial).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote praying before entering Montesinos' cave
22.2 Adventure of the cave of Montesinos

Before entering Montesinos' cave, don Quixote prays imploring God to aid him and grant him success in this new perilous adventure; Sancho and the licenciate's cousin observe him and hold a rope tied to don Quixote.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote talking to one of the two companions of Dulcinea in Montesinos' cave
23.2 DQ encounter with the enchanted Dulcinea in the cave

In Montesinos' cave, don Quixote encounters one of the two companions of the enchanted Dulcinea; the damsel asks don Quixote to lend her half a dozen reals on a new dimity petticoat.Gestures and details (see the petticoat) are well represented in accordance with Cervantes' text.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote talking to the braying mayors squadron
Don Quixote, surrounded by the men of the braying mayors squadron, begins to talk to them.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
After the adventure with the braying mayors squadron, don Quixote dismounts to examine Sancho's wounds.Both figures are resolved with great mastery
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho falling from their mounts
30.1 DQ and SP meet the Duchess
Humorous moment of don Quixote and Sancho's encounter with the Duchess; when don Quixote is going to dismount, he falls to the ground; in the background, Sancho has fallen too.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Arrival of four damsels to wash don Quixote's beard
Four damsels arrive before the Duke, Duchess and don Quixote to wash don Quixote's beard.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.2 - The signature "B.v." may refer to the engraver Louis-Henri Breviere.
Don Quixote, the Duke and Duchess during the hunt of the wild boar
Don Quixote, the Duke and Duchess hunting the wild boar.See Duke and Duchess' gestures; accurate to Cervantes' text: "a todos se adelantara la duquesa, si el duque no se lo estorbara" (34:2).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho agrees to lash himself and don Quixote thanks him
35.1 Merlin’s prophecy about Dulcinea and remedy for her enchantment
When Sancho agrees to lash himself to disenchant Dulcinea, don Quixote hangs on his neck and kisses him again and again on his forehead and cheeks; the Duke and Duchess observe them.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
38.1 Trifaldi’s story38.2 Arrival of Countess Trifaldi

Arrival of the Countess Trifaldi accompanied by Trifaldín; accurate to Cervantes' text, three pages hold each point of her skirt.Countess Trifaldi's gesture and face, moaning, are remarkable, but Johannot has forgotten that she has to appear bearded(!).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho find a lance with a parchment

After their "flight" with Clavileño, don Quixote and Sancho perceive a lance planted in the ground with a parchment; in it, it is announced the end of Countess Trifaldi's adventure; several servants pretend to be fainted on the ground.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote giving advices to Sancho
42.1 Advice of DQ to SP, as governor of Barataria

Excellent image of don Quixote giving advice to Sancho before leaving for Barataria Island.See the gestures of both figures, they are very remarkable (especially Sancho, listening with great attention).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho on the road to Barataria Island

Sancho, mounted on a mule and dressed as a lawyer, setts off for Barataria Island attended by a great number of people and followed by his donkey.Sancho's image has a combination of dignity and parody.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho asking to the pig dealer

Sancho asks to the pig dealer (accused of having forced the woman on the right) if he has any money to pay her.The figures of the pig dealer and the accusing woman, although they are not so detailed as the figures in the foreground, are absulutely remarkable (see the bored gesture of the woman).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote bandaged during doña Rodríguez' visit
48.1 Doña Rodríguez visits DQ at night in his room
Detailed and almost caricature representation of don Quixote; reference to his monologue about the dueñas while doña Rodríguez is gone to light her candle.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho stops the duel between two men
49.1 SP in Barataria49.2 SP finds two men duelling

During the night rounds, Sancho, accompanied by the majordomo, secretary, head-carver, chronicler, alguacils and notaries, finds two men fighting; one of the men (see his gesture) accuses the other of trying to rob him.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
The Duchess' page asking to some women washing in a brook
50.1 Duchess’s page takes letter and presents to SP’s wife

The Duchess' page finds some women washing in a brook and asks them whether they know where Teresa Panza lives (one of the women is Teresa Panza's daughter, Sanchica or Mari Sancha).Scene with good drawing (see the women in the foreground or the gesture of the page) and engraving.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
A friar writing two letters for Teresa Panza
50.1 Duchess’s page takes letter and presents to SP’s wife

Teresa Panza asks a friar to write two letters, one for her husband and another one for the Duchess, giving him a cake and two eggs (see the detail).The figure of the friar is especially remarkable (face, gesture, clothes...).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Sancho fallen on the ground and bound between two shields
Sancho, bound tight between two large shields, falls to the ground and the soldiers continue fighting over him.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote hearing Sancho's voice from a pit
Passing by the mouth of a pit, don Quixote, mounted on Rocinante, hears Sancho's voice.Drawing and engraving are excellent (notice don Quixote's gesture, looking into the pit).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho leaving the Duke's palace
57.1 DQ leaves duke’s palace57.2 Altisidora’s false love for DQ
Don Quixote and Sancho leaves the Duke's palace and the servants bid them farewell (among the servants, it appears Altisidora).
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote and Sancho trampled by bulls
A drove of bulls tramples don Quixote and Sancho (scene in the background without too many details).The figure of the herdsman in the left foreground is especially remarkable.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
One bandit raising his harquebuss against Sancho
60.2 DQ meets Roque Guinart, the bandit, on his way to Barcelona

The action described by Cervantes has been perfectly represented through different gestures: first, one of the bandits raises his harquebuss against Sancho; then, the squire is frightened out of his wits; and finally, Roque orders the bandit to put the harquebuss down.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
62.2 DQ with his name on his back
During don Quixote's stroll in Barcelona, they put a parchment with his name on don Quixote's back, so everybody recognizes him and points to him.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote stepping on board of a skiff
Don Quixote steps on board of a skiff covered with rich carpets and cushions; the illustration, very accurate to Cervantes' text, presents an image of don Quixote with dignity.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
Don Quixote carried in a carrying chair
64.1 DQ is defeated by the Knight of the White Moon (Sansón Carrasco)
After being defeated by the Knight of the White Moon, don Quixote is carried into the city in a carrying chair.Notice Sancho's silhouette, weeping.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
69.1 DQ and SP back the Dukes´ palace69.2 Altisidora’s mock death and resurrection

Detailed representation of Sancho dressed with the clothes for Altisidora's resurrection: a robe of black buckram painted all over with flames of fire and a mitre painted with devils (some kind of bats in the illustration). This mitre, which should be such as those undergoing the sentece of the Holy Office wear (capirote), has been represented more like a bishop mitre.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
71.1 SP accepts to give himself lashes for money to disenchant Dulcinea
After agreeing a price with don Quixote, Sancho whips himself while don Quixote (in the background) counts the lashes.Notice Sancho's cunning expression; he is not whipping himself, but the tree.
1 - Same illustration first published in Paris: Dubochet, 1836-37.
